      <p align=3D"center" style=3D"margin-left: 11px; margin-right: 11px"=
>
<strong><font face=3D"Verdana" size=3D"4" color=3D"#FF0000">
Background:</font></strong></p>
		<p align=3D"left" style=3D"margin-left: 11px; margin-right: 11px">
<font face=3D"Verdana" size=3D"2">This course introduces principles and m=
ethods of=20
market-based valuation and risk management. Familiarity with these princi=
ples=20
and methods is now essential to managing all of the major resources and=
=20
commitments in the electric power industry, including fuel and power purc=
hase=20
contracts, generation resources, retail service agreements, and regulator=
y=20
policies (e.g., Provider of Last Resort obligations). Participants will s=
tudy=20
the financial "building blocks" -- elementary forward and option contract=
s.=20
Trainers will explain how the value and risk of non-financial contracts a=
nd=20
physical assets can be understood in terms of equivalent combinations of=
=20
elementary contracts. With these principles, participants will study meth=
ods for=20
valuing forward contracts and options, both simple and complex; modeling=
=20
uncertainty in market prices; and estimating volatility. Finally, partici=
pants=20
will learn about the basic risk management strategies, as well as how to=
=20
calculate risk exposures and measure portfolio risk.</font></p>
		<p align=3D"center" style=3D"margin-left: 11px; margin-right: 11px">
<i><b><font face=3D"Verdana" size=3D"2">Register today!</font></b></i></p=
>
		<font face=3D"Verdana" size=3D"2">
      <font face=3D"Verdana" size=3D"4" color=3D"#FF0000">
		<p align=3D"center" style=3D"margin-left: 11px; margin-right: 11px">
<strong>Workshop Outline:</strong></p>
      </font>
      <p align=3D"left" style=3D"margin-left: 11px; margin-right: 11px">=

		<b>The course addresses concepts, instruments, and methods for measurin=
g=20
		and managing risk in energy commodity markets. A series of exercises=20
		will be included to reinforce the main ideas.<br />
		Topics include:<br />
		</b>. Basic forward and option contracts<br />
		. Relationship of complex contracts and physical assets to basic=20
		contracts<br />
		. Valuing forward contracts and estimating forward prices<br />
		. Valuing simple option contracts<br />
		. Modeling price uncertainty and estimating volatility<br />
		. Methods for valuing complex options<br />
		. Basic risk management strategies<br />
		. Measuring and managing portfolio risk<br />
		&nbsp;</p>
      </font>
      <font face=3D"Verdana" size=3D"4" color=3D"#FF0000">
		<p align=3D"center" style=3D"margin-left: 11px; margin-right: 11px">
<strong>Who Should Attend:</strong></p>
      </font>
      <font face=3D"Verdana" size=3D"2">
		<p align=3D"left" style=3D"margin-left: 11px; margin-right: 11px">
<b>This course should be of interest to staff with responsibilities in th=
e=20
following areas:<br />
</b>. Power and fuel procurement<br />
. Generation planning<br />
. Retail services<br />
. Regulatory policy<br />
. Energy trading and marketing<br />
. Treasury and corporate finance<br />
. Corporate strategy<br />
<b>Class size will be limited to 25 attendees on a first-come, first-serv=
e=20
basis. This is an intensive, skill-building class in which participants w=
ill=20
work through numerous examples with the aid of paper, pencil, and hand-he=
ld=20
calculators.</b></p>
		<p align=3D"left" style=3D"margin-left: 11px; margin-right: 11px">
<b>Prior training in financial economics is NOT required. The Value &amp;=
 Risk in=20
Energy Markets workshop begins at 8:30 a.m. on day one and concludes at n=
oon on=20
day three.</b></p>
      </font>
      <font face=3D"Verdana" size=3D"4" color=3D"#FF0000">
		<p align=3D"center" style=3D"margin-left: 11px; margin-right: 11px">
<strong>Course Instructor:</strong></p>
      </font>
      <font face=3D"Verdana" size=3D"2">
		<p align=3D"left" style=3D"margin-left: 11px; margin-right: 11px">
<b>Art Altman</b><br />
<b>Program Manager, EPRI's Value &amp; Risk in Energy Markets<br />
</b>Art's background is in finance and information technology, and his fo=
cus at=20
EPRI is on R&amp;D in risk management and asset valuation. He helps EPRI =
member=20
companies value contracts and assets and manage the financial risks that =
they=20
face in competitive power<br />
markets. Art is currently the manager of EPRI's Energy Book System, an=20
integrated suite of software tools for valuation and risk management. He =
has an=20
M.B.A. from the University of California at Berkeley, and an M.S. from th=
e=20
University of Rochester. Email: aaltman@epri.com</p>
      </font>
